-- Sub-Saharan African Equities: East African Cables, Equity Bank Are Active
-- Eric Ombok
-- 2010-07-19T13:55:15Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-19/sub-saharan-african-equities-east-african-cables-equity-bank-are-active.html

          
          
             Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  declined
for a second day, retreating 0.2 percent to close at 1,686.02 as
of 1:30 p.m. in Port Louis.  
 Kenya’s  All-Share Index  snapped two days of gains, dropping
0.1 percent to 75.65 as of 2:05 p.m. in Nairobi. The  Nigerian
Stock Exchange All-Share Index  retreated 0.4 percent to
24.801.15 at 12:39 p.m. in Lagos, while Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia
Overall Index  dropped for a fourth day, decreasing 0.1 percent
to 757.34 as of 2:04 p.m. in Windhoek. The  Ghana Stock Exchange
All-Share Index  surged the most in almost a month, climbing 1.8
percent to close at 6,270.27 as of 1 p.m. in Accra.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 East African Cables Ltd.  (EACL KN), the region’s biggest
cable manufacturer, fell the most in more than six years,
dropping 2.8 shillings, or 13 percent, to 18.95 shillings. The
Kenyan company’s Tanzanian unit will post a “significant”
first-half loss because of provisions for bad and doubtful debts
and inventory, it said in a statement distributed by the Nairobi
Stock Exchange today.  
 Equity Bank Ltd.  (EQBNK KN), Kenya’s biggest lender, rose
to the highest in two weeks, gaining 25 cents, or 1.1 percent,
to 23.75 shillings. CFC Stanbic Financial Services Ltd.
speculated the company will report an increase of 50 percent to
60 percent in earnings for the first half through June, Judd
Murigi, head of research at Nairobi-based CFC, said in a phone
interview today.  
 Equity Bank will announce its half-year earnings tomorrow,
it said in an e-mailed statement on July 16.  
